Chippenham, Wiltshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1395–1430":"1395–1430","1381–1478":"1381–1478","1415–1478":"1415–1478","1418–Male":"1418–Deceased","1430–1478":"1430–1478","–1468":"–1468","1365–1434":"1365–1434","1373–1428":"1373–1428","1415":"1415","1468":"1468","about 1418":"about 1418","1434":"1434","1478":"1478","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","1381":"1381","1418":"1418","1428":"1428","Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England":"Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England","Sawbridge, Little Berkhanstead, Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England":"Broxbourne, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Broxbourne was born in 1395, in Chippen